    "topic": "event-driven",
    "pivots": [
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1504,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 802,
      "chipText": "→ at-least-once plus an idempotent consumer, never exactly-once delivery\nThe broker retries until acked, so it never drops but may duplicate. Exactly-once delivery isn't achievable across a network; at-least-once plus a dedup check gives effectively-once processing, which is the honest answer.",
      "chipLen": 294,
      "chipW": 1410,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 66,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     },
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1176,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 474,
      "chipText": "→ a max-receive count into a dead-letter queue\nA poison message cycled forever would jam the queue. After N attempts it moves to a DLQ where it can be inspected and replayed, so one bad payload can never block the pipeline.",
      "chipLen": 223,
      "chipW": 1097,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 51,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "topic": "stream-batch-processing",
    "pivots": [
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 2058,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 1356,
      "chipText": "→ by freshness requirement: hours-fine -> batch (simple, exact, high-throughput); seconds-matter -> stream (low-latency, windowed)\nBatch for bounded data where staleness is acceptable (reports, ETL, analytics) -- simpler and exact; stream when results must reflect events within seconds (fraud, alerting, live dashboards) -- and consider micro-batch as the middle ground before paying full streaming complexity.",
      "chipLen": 411,
      "chipW": 1984,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 46,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     },
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 2168,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 1466,
      "chipText": "→ window by event-time, fire on watermarks, and set an allowed-lateness policy (update / drop / side-output)\nEvent-time windowing is correct but forces late-data handling: a watermark (event-time-so-far) decides when a window fires, allowed-lateness restates results for stragglers within a grace period, and very-late events are dropped or side-output for reconciliation -- explicitly choosing the completeness/latency/complexity trade.",
      "chipLen": 437,
      "chipW": 2100,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 40,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "topic": "shared-definition",
    "pivots": [
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1526,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 824,
      "chipText": "→ one table keyed by entity_type plus entity_id, at the cost of a real FK\nOne table serves every entity kind and keeps resolution uniform. The price is that the polymorphic pair can't have a true foreign key, so you enforce existence in the app or switch to separate nullable FK columns with a CHECK.",
      "chipLen": 300,
      "chipW": 1423,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 75,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     },
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1709,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 1007,
      "chipText": "→ yes, and it is the right tool when the attribute set is variable\nEntity, attribute, value is EAV. It's correct when attributes are tenant-defined or open-ended, where columns would need a migration each; it's wrong for a fixed schema, where typed columns are simpler and safer. Owning that it's EAV, and validating on write, is the mature answer.",
      "chipLen": 348,
      "chipW": 1652,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 29,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "topic": "retries-timeouts",
    "pivots": [
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1310,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 608,
      "chipText": "→ from the dependency's latency distribution -- above p99 with margin\nToo short manufactures failures on healthy-but-slow calls; too long lets a hung dependency exhaust your pool before it fires. Set it from real p99, and set connect/read/total separately.",
      "chipLen": 256,
      "chipW": 1235,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 47,
      "pivOverflowHidden": "hidden"
     },
     {
      "pivW": 704,
      "sumScrollW": 1299,
      "sumClientW": 702,
      "overflow": 597,
      "chipText": "→ yes -- that's a retry storm; cap with backoff, jitter, budgets, and a circuit-breaker\nRetries add load exactly when the dependency is struggling, multiplied across layers; under sustained overload you fail fast and shed load instead of retrying harder.",
      "chipLen": 254,
      "chipW": 1199,
      "chipNowrap": "nowrap",
      "paText": "",
      "paLen": 0,
      "paEmpty": true,
      "pqW": 72,
